issue.title: Must persist counter across restarts
issue.body:
**As a**  service provider,  
 **I need** the service to persist the last known count
 **So that** users don't lose track of their counts after the service is restarted
   
 ### Details and Assumptions
 * We will use a Redis Database
 * Counter will be used as a name-value pair
   
 ### Acceptance Criteria  
   
 ```gherkin
 Given I have incremented the counter to 2
 When I restart the service
 Then the counter should still return 2
 ```

comment.body:
The zoom logic appears inverted. When distance is greater than the threshold (user is far), it keeps the current zoom level, but when distance is less than the threshold (user is close), it uses Math.Max which could zoom out instead of in. This contradicts the typical expectation that being close should result in higher zoom levels.
```suggestion
        var targetZoomLevel = distance > closeDistanceThresholdKM ? currentZoomLevel : CLOSE_ZOOM_LEVEL;
```

comment.body: Do we really want these to be generated though?  The perspective I approached this from was to treat the `ScriptEntry` labels and matching header values not as constants, but instead as though they were effectively equivalent to functions that can be externally called, just in a .s file instead of in a .c file.  With that in mind, manually maintaining the function/label definitions in a matching .h file, instead of generating them, becomes the intuitive approach.

issue.title: [Feature]: Refactor class components to functional components
issue.body:
### Requirement

Jaeger UI still have a number of core components that are React class-based components. This prevents the use of hooks in them, and newest DX on them.

Refactor all the possible components in Jaeger UI that still are class-based components. Convert them to functional components, whenever possible.

### Problem & Motivation

The idea is also while moving to them, use hooks to abstract the functionality present in Redux and in data fetching so in a near future we can easily switch using the hooks to use other props provider.

### Proposal & Implementation
Refactor should be done carefully and providing tests where they do not exist. The lifecycle of the components should be preserved while watching out for edge cases and UX problems.

## Deliverables
IMO It should be delivered all at once, as a major breaking change. Ideally, we won't change the contract of any of the components, so no new props passed down, no return anything to the tree that we were not returning before, unless it's justified.

If the contract has to be broken, then it must be properly documented and exposed in the upgrade guide.

Here there is a preliminary list as of Jun 7 2025:


issue.title: Allow to configure schema in postgres driver
issue.body:
Thanks for this great piece of software!

I'd like to propose an improvement:

I'm using the same Postgres database (in Supabase) for sidequest and the rest of my application. While sidequest takes care of its tables automatically, my application's tables are managed with Drizzle ORM. This leads to a collision whenever I deploy a new schema, because I don't have schemas defined for the sidequest tables, therefore Drizzle wants to delete them.

It would be great if I could tell sidequest to use its own schema for its tables.

I know that some Postgres drives support selecting the schema by appending `?currentSchema=sidequest` to the connection url. This would be a simple solution, but this does not work with Supabase.

Therefore it would be great if I could configure the schema in the sidequest config:

```typescript
  Sidequest.configure({
    backend: {
      driver: '@sidequest/postgres-backend',
      config: process.env.DATABASE_URL,
      schema: 'sidequest' // proposed new entry. Optional, defaults to 'public'
    }
  })
```

I couldn't find any config entry like this, so I propose to add it.

Let me know what you think about this or if there already is a solution that I'm not aware of.

Cheers
Fred

comment.body:
Thx for the quick response.

I think the issue for me was that `BackendConfig.config` is of type `unknown`, so I get no hint that this could be an object (and of course I will get no hint about the shape of that object either) and all examples in the docs are with a connection string only.

The tip is in the docs (thanks for pointing it out) but easily read over.

It would be great to have proper type hints for the config and also an actual example in the docs.
